Dist-over-time-by-site

Dan Spakowicz

6/22/2022

From Xin:

As we discussed, there is the raw data for our figure 3b. It can be loaded into R by load(path_to_the_file). The variable you need will be dist which is the bray Curtis distance, and diffdays which is the time interval. We kept all other variables like batch or season so you can decide if this is something important in your model. There are two questions we want to answer in figure 3, 1) if the stool microbiome are the most stable one across time? 2) when one body site is not so stable (over time), does another body site also being unstable? We answered this a little bit in figure 3c, but would appreciate if you have additional ways to test or model this.

all %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = dist)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = dataset))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

all2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = dist)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = dataset))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

all2v2 <- 
  all2%>%
  mutate(dist.0.99 = if_else(dist == 1,
                             true = 0.9999999999999999,
                             false = dist),
         dist_log = log10(dist.0.99),
         dist_neglogRec = -log10(1 - dist.0.99),
         dist_logneglogRec = log10(dist_neglogRec),
         dist_sqrt = sqrt(dist),
         dist_logit = log(dist.0.99 / (1-dist.0.99)),
         dist_asin = asin(sqrt(dist))
         )

# all.trans$dist[all.trans$dist == 1] <- 0.9999999999999999
# 
# all.trans <- all.trans %>% mutate(dist_trans = log10(-log10(1-dist)))
all2v2 %>%
  select(dataset, contains("dist")) %>%
  gather(-dataset, key = "measure", value = "value") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = dataset)) +
  facet_wrap(~measure, scales = "free")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
